{
  "version": "2.1.0",
  "$schema": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oasis-tcs/sarif-spec/master/Schemata/sarif-schema-2.1.0.json",
  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "Barrys Special AI Vuln Audit",
          "version": "1.0.0",
          "informationUri": "https://github.com/joesnipes/juice-shop",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-001",
              "name": "SQL Injection / Authentication Bypass in login endpoint",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "SQL Injection / Authentication Bypass in login endpoint"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "POST /rest/user/login passes req.body.email directly into a raw template literal SQL query. Sending email='\\' OR 1=1--' is a textbook tautology bypass that returns the first row (the admin) and the route then issues a JWT for that user via security.authorize(). No parameterization, no escaping, no allow-list. The result is full admin takeover from an entirely unauthenticated request."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Use parameterized queries via Sequelize replacements/bind (e.g. UserModel.findOne({ where: { email, password: hashedPw } })) and migrate password handling to bcrypt/argon2. Never interpolate untrusted strings into raw SQL.",
                "markdown": "## SQL Injection / Authentication Bypass in login endpoint\n\n**CWE:** CWE-89\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\nPOST /rest/user/login passes req.body.email directly into a raw template literal SQL query. Sending email='\\' OR 1=1--' is a textbook tautology bypass that returns the first row (the admin) and the route then issues a JWT for that user via security.authorize(). No parameterization, no escaping, no allow-list. The result is full admin takeover from an entirely unauthenticated request.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nUse parameterized queries via Sequelize replacements/bind (e.g. UserModel.findOne({ where: { email, password: hashedPw } })) and migrate password handling to bcrypt/argon2. Never interpolate untrusted strings into raw SQL."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.8",
                "tags": [
                  "sql_injection",
                  "auth_bypass",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-89"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A03:2021-Injection"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-002",
              "name": "UNION SQL Injection in unauthenticated product search",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "UNION SQL Injection in unauthenticated product search"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "GET /rest/products/search?q= is reachable without authentication and concatenates the query parameter directly into raw SQL. Because the database is SQLite the attacker can append a UNION SELECT statement to exfiltrate Users (emails, MD5 password hashes) and sqlite_master (table schemas). The route code itself solves a 'unionSqlInjectionChallenge' by detecting if user rows leak via this primitive, which proves it is exploitable end-to-end."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Use Sequelize replacements/bind (`:criteria`) or ProductModel.findAll({ where: { [Op.or]: [{ name: { [Op.like]: q } }, ...] } }). The 200-byte truncation does not prevent injection.",
                "markdown": "## UNION SQL Injection in unauthenticated product search\n\n**CWE:** CWE-89\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\nGET /rest/products/search?q= is reachable without authentication and concatenates the query parameter directly into raw SQL. Because the database is SQLite the attacker can append a UNION SELECT statement to exfiltrate Users (emails, MD5 password hashes) and sqlite_master (table schemas). The route code itself solves a 'unionSqlInjectionChallenge' by detecting if user rows leak via this primitive, which proves it is exploitable end-to-end.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nUse Sequelize replacements/bind (`:criteria`) or ProductModel.findAll({ where: { [Op.or]: [{ name: { [Op.like]: q } }, ...] } }). The 200-byte truncation does not prevent injection."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.1",
                "tags": [
                  "sql_injection",
                  "info_disclosure",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-89"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A03:2021-Injection"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-003",
              "name": "Hard-coded RSA private key used to sign all JWTs",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Hard-coded RSA private key used to sign all JWTs"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The full 1024-bit RSA private key used by security.authorize() to sign all session JWTs (RS256) is checked into source. Anyone who reads the public GitHub repo can mint a JWT with `data.role=\"admin\"` for any user id and bypass every authentication and authorization check in the application. The matching `encryptionkeys/jwt.pub` is the corresponding public key used for verification. This is the single most catastrophic finding."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Generate a fresh RSA-2048 (or Ed25519) key pair at deploy time, store the private key in a secret manager (KMS/Vault/SSM), rotate immediately, and revoke any tokens minted under the leaked key.",
                "markdown": "## Hard-coded RSA private key used to sign all JWTs\n\n**CWE:** CWE-798\n\n**OWASP:** A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures\n\n### Exploitation\n\nThe full 1024-bit RSA private key used by security.authorize() to sign all session JWTs (RS256) is checked into source. Anyone who reads the public GitHub repo can mint a JWT with `data.role=\"admin\"` for any user id and bypass every authentication and authorization check in the application. The matching `encryptionkeys/jwt.pub` is the corresponding public key used for verification. This is the single most catastrophic finding.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nGenerate a fresh RSA-2048 (or Ed25519) key pair at deploy time, store the private key in a secret manager (KMS/Vault/SSM), rotate immediately, and revoke any tokens minted under the leaked key."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.8",
                "tags": [
                  "hardcoded_secret",
                  "jwt_forgery",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-004",
              "name": "MD5 used as password hash with no salt",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "MD5 used as password hash with no salt"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "User passwords are stored as bare MD5 hashes (no salt, no key-stretching). MD5 is broken for password hashing — modern GPUs hash hundreds of GH/s. Combined with the UNION SQLi (JS-AUDIT-002), every password becomes trivially crackable by rainbow tables / hashcat. Even without SQLi, the hashing function is used in 'authorize'-equivalent flows server-side."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Switch to bcrypt (cost >= 12), argon2id, or scrypt with per-user salt. Rehash on next login.",
                "markdown": "## MD5 used as password hash with no salt\n\n**CWE:** CWE-916\n\n**OWASP:** A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures\n\n### Exploitation\n\nUser passwords are stored as bare MD5 hashes (no salt, no key-stretching). MD5 is broken for password hashing — modern GPUs hash hundreds of GH/s. Combined with the UNION SQLi (JS-AUDIT-002), every password becomes trivially crackable by rainbow tables / hashcat. Even without SQLi, the hashing function is used in 'authorize'-equivalent flows server-side.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nSwitch to bcrypt (cost >= 12), argon2id, or scrypt with per-user salt. Rehash on next login."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.2",
                "tags": [
                  "weak_crypto",
                  "password_hash",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-916"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-005",
              "name": "Hard-coded HMAC secret used for security-answer verification",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Hard-coded HMAC secret used for security-answer verification"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Security-answer 'hashes' in SecurityAnswers table are HMAC-SHA256 with a static, public secret. With the secret in the repo any attacker who reads the SecurityAnswers row can precompute HMACs offline (or just submit known answers) to reset a victim's password via /rest/user/reset-password (routes/resetPassword.ts:41 compares `security.hmac(answer) === data.answer`). It also disables HMAC's collision resistance assumption."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Move secret to env/secret manager; rotate. Long-term, do not rely on security questions; require a verified-email token flow instead.",
                "markdown": "## Hard-coded HMAC secret used for security-answer verification\n\n**CWE:** CWE-798\n\n**OWASP:** A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures\n\n### Exploitation\n\nSecurity-answer 'hashes' in SecurityAnswers table are HMAC-SHA256 with a static, public secret. With the secret in the repo any attacker who reads the SecurityAnswers row can precompute HMACs offline (or just submit known answers) to reset a victim's password via /rest/user/reset-password (routes/resetPassword.ts:41 compares `security.hmac(answer) === data.answer`). It also disables HMAC's collision resistance assumption.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nMove secret to env/secret manager; rotate. Long-term, do not rely on security questions; require a verified-email token flow instead."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.1",
                "tags": [
                  "hardcoded_secret",
                  "weak_crypto",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A02:2021-Cryptographic Failures"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-006",
              "name": "express-jwt 0.1.3 + jsonwebtoken 0.4.0 — alg:none / verification bypass",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "express-jwt 0.1.3 + jsonwebtoken 0.4.0 — alg:none / verification bypass"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "package.json pins express-jwt@0.1.3 and jsonwebtoken@0.4.0 — both are wildly out of date. express-jwt prior to 5.3.3 (GHSA-6cwn-77pq-3fpx) does not enforce `algorithms`, so an attacker can craft a token with header `alg:none` (no signature) and bypass auth on every middleware-protected route. jsonwebtoken<=4.2.1 has the original verification-bypass CVE. Combined with the hardcoded public key being downloadable from /encryptionkeys/jwt.pub, the attacker can also forge HS256 tokens signed with the public key as a symmetric secret."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Upgrade express-jwt to >=8.x (passing `algorithms: ['RS256']`) and jsonwebtoken to >=9.x. Pin algorithm explicitly.",
                "markdown": "## express-jwt 0.1.3 + jsonwebtoken 0.4.0 — alg:none / verification bypass\n\n**CWE:** CWE-327\n\n**OWASP:** A06:2021-Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n\n### Exploitation\n\npackage.json pins express-jwt@0.1.3 and jsonwebtoken@0.4.0 — both are wildly out of date. express-jwt prior to 5.3.3 (GHSA-6cwn-77pq-3fpx) does not enforce `algorithms`, so an attacker can craft a token with header `alg:none` (no signature) and bypass auth on every middleware-protected route. jsonwebtoken<=4.2.1 has the original verification-bypass CVE. Combined with the hardcoded public key being downloadable from /encryptionkeys/jwt.pub, the attacker can also forge HS256 tokens signed with the public key as a symmetric secret.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nUpgrade express-jwt to >=8.x (passing `algorithms: ['RS256']`) and jsonwebtoken to >=9.x. Pin algorithm explicitly."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.1",
                "tags": [
                  "vulnerable_dependency",
                  "auth_bypass",
                  "jwt_alg_confusion",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A06:2021-Vulnerable and Outdated Components"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-007",
              "name": "denyAll() relies on Math.random() as JWT verification secret",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "denyAll() relies on Math.random() as JWT verification secret"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`denyAll` is wired into critical routes (PUT/DELETE /api/Users/:id, DELETE /api/Products/:id, /api/Challenges, /api/Hints, /api/SecurityQuestions, /api/Recycles/:id, etc.). Because of the express-jwt 0.1.3 alg:none bug above, a token with `alg:none` would skip secret validation entirely. Even without that, Math.random() is non-cryptographic and predictable; an attacker who can guess one secret can mint tokens. The bigger issue is that 'deny all' is implemented as 'verify with a random secret' instead of a hard 403, which is fundamentally wrong."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Replace with an explicit middleware that always returns 403: `(req,res)=>res.status(403).end()`. Do not rely on the JWT layer at all.",
                "markdown": "## denyAll() relies on Math.random() as JWT verification secret\n\n**CWE:** CWE-330\n\n**OWASP:** A07:2021-Identification and Authentication Failures\n\n### Exploitation\n\n`denyAll` is wired into critical routes (PUT/DELETE /api/Users/:id, DELETE /api/Products/:id, /api/Challenges, /api/Hints, /api/SecurityQuestions, /api/Recycles/:id, etc.). Because of the express-jwt 0.1.3 alg:none bug above, a token with `alg:none` would skip secret validation entirely. Even without that, Math.random() is non-cryptographic and predictable; an attacker who can guess one secret can mint tokens. The bigger issue is that 'deny all' is implemented as 'verify with a random secret' instead of a hard 403, which is fundamentally wrong.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nReplace with an explicit middleware that always returns 403: `(req,res)=>res.status(403).end()`. Do not rely on the JWT layer at all."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "7.5",
                "tags": [
                  "insecure_randomness",
                  "auth_bypass",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-330"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A07:2021-Identification and Authentication Failures"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-008",
              "name": "Open-redirect allowlist uses substring match (url.includes)",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Open-redirect allowlist uses substring match (url.includes)"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "isRedirectAllowed() returns true if the *attacker-supplied URL* contains an allowlisted string anywhere. Therefore `/redirect?to=https://evil.example.com/?x=https://github.com/juice-shop/juice-shop` passes the check and the server returns a 302 to evil.example.com. Used for phishing / credential harvesting / token exfil. CodeQL (alert 3) confirms."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Parse with `new URL(toUrl)` and compare `url.origin` against an allowlist of full origins; or use signed redirect tokens.",
                "markdown": "## Open-redirect allowlist uses substring match (url.includes)\n\n**CWE:** CWE-601\n\n**OWASP:** A01:2021-Broken Access Control\n\n### Exploitation\n\nisRedirectAllowed() returns true if the *attacker-supplied URL* contains an allowlisted string anywhere. Therefore `/redirect?to=https://evil.example.com/?x=https://github.com/juice-shop/juice-shop` passes the check and the server returns a 302 to evil.example.com. Used for phishing / credential harvesting / token exfil. CodeQL (alert 3) confirms.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nParse with `new URL(toUrl)` and compare `url.origin` against an allowlist of full origins; or use signed redirect tokens."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "7.4",
                "tags": [
                  "open_redirect",
                  "tier1",
                  "tier3"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A01:2021-Broken Access Control"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-009",
              "name": "Pug SSTI + eval() on username + user-controlled CSP -> RCE/XSS",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Pug SSTI + eval() on username + user-controlled CSP -> RCE/XSS"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The route reads the logged-in user's own username from the DB. If it matches `#{...}` the inner expression is passed to JavaScript `eval()` *server-side*. Any authenticated user can therefore execute arbitrary Node.js code in the server process by updating their own username via PATCH /api/Users/:id or POST /profile. Additionally, the `profileImage` field is interpolated unsanitised into a Content-Security-Policy header (line 88), letting the same user weaken/override CSP and achieve persistent XSS. This is full server-side RCE."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Never eval user data. Render usernames with HTML-escape only (Handlebars/Angular auto-escape). Build CSP from a static template, never interpolate user input.",
                "markdown": "## Pug SSTI + eval() on username + user-controlled CSP -> RCE/XSS\n\n**CWE:** CWE-94\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\nThe route reads the logged-in user's own username from the DB. If it matches `#{...}` the inner expression is passed to JavaScript `eval()` *server-side*. Any authenticated user can therefore execute arbitrary Node.js code in the server process by updating their own username via PATCH /api/Users/:id or POST /profile. Additionally, the `profileImage` field is interpolated unsanitised into a Content-Security-Policy header (line 88), letting the same user weaken/override CSP and achieve persistent XSS. This is full server-side RCE.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nNever eval user data. Render usernames with HTML-escape only (Handlebars/Angular auto-escape). Build CSP from a static template, never interpolate user input."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.6",
                "tags": [
                  "ssti",
                  "code_injection",
                  "xss",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-94"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A03:2021-Injection"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-010",
              "name": "B2B order safeEval (notevil) used inside vm with attacker-controlled body -> RCE/DoS",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "B2B order safeEval (notevil) used inside vm with attacker-controlled body -> RCE/DoS"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`notevil` (1.3.3) has had multiple documented sandbox escapes (e.g. accessing constructor chains via prototype lookups to reach `Function('return process')()`). It is not a security boundary. With the hardcoded RSA key (JS-AUDIT-003) an attacker can mint a B2B token, then POST {orderLinesData: \"<payload>\"} to /b2b/v2/orders and obtain RCE. Even without escape, infinite-loop / billion-laughs style payloads trigger reliable DoS (the code itself acknowledges this with rceOccupyChallenge)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Do not evaluate user-supplied code. Accept structured JSON only and validate against a schema. If business logic genuinely requires expressions, run them in a separate sandboxed worker with strict CPU/memory budgets — preferably as data, not code.",
                "markdown": "## B2B order safeEval (notevil) used inside vm with attacker-controlled body -> RCE/DoS\n\n**CWE:** CWE-94\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\n`notevil` (1.3.3) has had multiple documented sandbox escapes (e.g. accessing constructor chains via prototype lookups to reach `Function('return process')()`). It is not a security boundary. With the hardcoded RSA key (JS-AUDIT-003) an attacker can mint a B2B token, then POST {orderLinesData: \"<payload>\"} to /b2b/v2/orders and obtain RCE. Even without escape, infinite-loop / billion-laughs style payloads trigger reliable DoS (the code itself acknowledges this with rceOccupyChallenge).\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nDo not evaluate user-supplied code. Accept structured JSON only and validate against a schema. If business logic genuinely requires expressions, run them in a separate sandboxed worker with strict CPU/memory budgets — preferably as data, not code."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.1",
                "tags": [
                  "code_injection",
                  "dos",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-94"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A03:2021-Injection"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-011",
              "name": "Zip-Slip / unbounded extraction in /file-upload (.zip handler)",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Zip-Slip / unbounded extraction in /file-upload (.zip handler)"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The check `absolutePath.includes(path.resolve('.'))` only ensures the resolved path *contains* the project root; it does NOT prevent traversal. An entry path like `../../../../../<projectRoot>/etc/whatever` would still satisfy the check on some layouts. Even if traversal were blocked, the stream destination uses the raw `fileName` from the zip entry (line 45) without sanitisation, so symlink overwrite of files under uploads/complaints is possible. There is also no decompressed-size limit (zip-bomb DoS)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Resolve each entry path with path.resolve(extractRoot, fileName) then require startsWith(extractRoot + path.sep). Enforce per-entry and total decompressed-size limits. Reject symlinks and absolute paths.",
                "markdown": "## Zip-Slip / unbounded extraction in /file-upload (.zip handler)\n\n**CWE:** CWE-22\n\n**OWASP:** A01:2021-Broken Access Control\n\n### Exploitation\n\nThe check `absolutePath.includes(path.resolve('.'))` only ensures the resolved path *contains* the project root; it does NOT prevent traversal. An entry path like `../../../../../<projectRoot>/etc/whatever` would still satisfy the check on some layouts. Even if traversal were blocked, the stream destination uses the raw `fileName` from the zip entry (line 45) without sanitisation, so symlink overwrite of files under uploads/complaints is possible. There is also no decompressed-size limit (zip-bomb DoS).\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nResolve each entry path with path.resolve(extractRoot, fileName) then require startsWith(extractRoot + path.sep). Enforce per-entry and total decompressed-size limits. Reject symlinks and absolute paths."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.1",
                "tags": [
                  "zip_slip",
                  "path_traversal",
                  "dos",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-22"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A01:2021-Broken Access Control"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-012",
              "name": "XXE via libxml.parseXml(data, { noent: true })",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "XXE via libxml.parseXml(data, { noent: true })"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`noent: true` enables external entity expansion. The code itself parses the result for /etc/passwd-style content (matchesEtcPasswdFile) confirming exploitability. Used for arbitrary local file disclosure (SYSTEM \"file:///etc/passwd\") and for billion-laughs DoS — both are acknowledged in source (xxeFileDisclosureChallenge / xxeDosChallenge)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Pass `noent: false`, disable DTD/external entities, or migrate to a JSON ingest. libxmljs2 also exposes a `replaceEntities` flag.",
                "markdown": "## XXE via libxml.parseXml(data, { noent: true })\n\n**CWE:** CWE-611\n\n**OWASP:** A05:2021-Security Misconfiguration\n\n### Exploitation\n\n`noent: true` enables external entity expansion. The code itself parses the result for /etc/passwd-style content (matchesEtcPasswdFile) confirming exploitability. Used for arbitrary local file disclosure (SYSTEM \"file:///etc/passwd\") and for billion-laughs DoS — both are acknowledged in source (xxeFileDisclosureChallenge / xxeDosChallenge).\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nPass `noent: false`, disable DTD/external entities, or migrate to a JSON ingest. libxmljs2 also exposes a `replaceEntities` flag."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.6",
                "tags": [
                  "xxe",
                  "info_disclosure",
                  "dos",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-611"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A05:2021-Security Misconfiguration"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-013",
              "name": "Unsafe YAML deserialization (yaml.load) with no size limit",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Unsafe YAML deserialization (yaml.load) with no size limit"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "js-yaml.load (vs safeLoad) historically supported custom tags that could instantiate JS objects; even modern versions allow YAML anchors causing exponential reference expansion (yaml-bomb). The route already detects yamlBombChallenge confirming DoS exploitability. The 200KB upload limit (server.ts:681) only bounds linear input — billion-laughs amplification is post-decode."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Use yaml.load with FAILSAFE_SCHEMA or yaml.safeLoad; reject anchors; cap output size; consider migrating to JSON.",
                "markdown": "## Unsafe YAML deserialization (yaml.load) with no size limit\n\n**CWE:** CWE-502\n\n**OWASP:** A08:2021-Software and Data Integrity Failures\n\n### Exploitation\n\njs-yaml.load (vs safeLoad) historically supported custom tags that could instantiate JS objects; even modern versions allow YAML anchors causing exponential reference expansion (yaml-bomb). The route already detects yamlBombChallenge confirming DoS exploitability. The 200KB upload limit (server.ts:681) only bounds linear input — billion-laughs amplification is post-decode.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nUse yaml.load with FAILSAFE_SCHEMA or yaml.safeLoad; reject anchors; cap output size; consider migrating to JSON."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "6.5",
                "tags": [
                  "unsafe_deserialization",
                  "dos",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-502"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A08:2021-Software and Data Integrity Failures"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-014",
              "name": "Admin role mass-assignment on POST /api/Users",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Admin role mass-assignment on POST /api/Users"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Registration is unauthenticated and goes through finale auto-CRUD. The model permits role in {customer, deluxe, accounting, admin}, and there is no whitelist of registration-permitted attributes. Posting {email, password, role:'admin'} creates an admin account directly. server.ts:407-419 even includes `registerAdminChallenge()` to *detect* this exploitation, confirming the route is exploitable."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Whitelist fields on registration (email, password only). Hardcode role='customer' server-side. Use finale's `excludeAttributes` for write paths or wrap with a dedicated registration handler.",
                "markdown": "## Admin role mass-assignment on POST /api/Users\n\n**CWE:** CWE-915\n\n**OWASP:** A04:2021-Insecure Design\n\n### Exploitation\n\nRegistration is unauthenticated and goes through finale auto-CRUD. The model permits role in {customer, deluxe, accounting, admin}, and there is no whitelist of registration-permitted attributes. Posting {email, password, role:'admin'} creates an admin account directly. server.ts:407-419 even includes `registerAdminChallenge()` to *detect* this exploitation, confirming the route is exploitable.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nWhitelist fields on registration (email, password only). Hardcode role='customer' server-side. Use finale's `excludeAttributes` for write paths or wrap with a dedicated registration handler."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "9.8",
                "tags": [
                  "mass_assignment",
                  "privilege_escalation",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-915"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A04:2021-Insecure Design"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-015",
              "name": "Finale auto-CRUD exposes write-access to every model",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Finale auto-CRUD exposes write-access to every model"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Finale exposes full CRUD on User, Product, Feedback, BasketItem, Complaint, Recycle, SecurityQuestion, SecurityAnswer, Address, PrivacyRequest, Card, Hint. Authorization is bolted on per-endpoint with a fragile mix of denyAll/isAuthorized; any missing entry (e.g. PUT /api/Products/:id is commented out at line 369) immediately becomes a privilege escalation. Customers can PATCH products, set their own prices, etc. The model itself permits role admin (see JS-AUDIT-014)."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Replace finale auto-CRUD with explicit hand-written routes and per-attribute authorization. At minimum, default-deny and explicitly enable only listed methods/fields.",
                "markdown": "## Finale auto-CRUD exposes write-access to every model\n\n**CWE:** CWE-284\n\n**OWASP:** A01:2021-Broken Access Control\n\n### Exploitation\n\nFinale exposes full CRUD on User, Product, Feedback, BasketItem, Complaint, Recycle, SecurityQuestion, SecurityAnswer, Address, PrivacyRequest, Card, Hint. Authorization is bolted on per-endpoint with a fragile mix of denyAll/isAuthorized; any missing entry (e.g. PUT /api/Products/:id is commented out at line 369) immediately becomes a privilege escalation. Customers can PATCH products, set their own prices, etc. The model itself permits role admin (see JS-AUDIT-014).\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nReplace finale auto-CRUD with explicit hand-written routes and per-attribute authorization. At minimum, default-deny and explicitly enable only listed methods/fields."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.1",
                "tags": [
                  "broken_access_control",
                  "tier1"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-284"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A01:2021-Broken Access Control"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-016",
              "name": "Directory listing of /ftp, /encryptionkeys, /support/logs",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Directory listing of /ftp, /encryptionkeys, /support/logs"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Three sensitive directories are publicly browseable: ftp/ contains incident-support.kdbx (KeePass db), package.json.bak, coupons_2013.md.bak, suspicious_errors.yml, encrypt.pyc; encryptionkeys/ exposes the JWT public key (used for forgery alongside JS-AUDIT-003) and premium.key; logs/ exposes raw morgan access logs. Combined with the file-serving routes' permissive allowlist (servePublicFiles allows .md/.pdf or the literal name 'incident-support.kdbx'), this is a direct data exfiltration channel."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Remove serveIndex calls and the public mounts entirely. Move secrets out of the repo. Restrict any operational endpoints to internal networks with auth.",
                "markdown": "## Directory listing of /ftp, /encryptionkeys, /support/logs\n\n**CWE:** CWE-548\n\n**OWASP:** A05:2021-Security Misconfiguration\n\n### Exploitation\n\nThree sensitive directories are publicly browseable: ftp/ contains incident-support.kdbx (KeePass db), package.json.bak, coupons_2013.md.bak, suspicious_errors.yml, encrypt.pyc; encryptionkeys/ exposes the JWT public key (used for forgery alongside JS-AUDIT-003) and premium.key; logs/ exposes raw morgan access logs. Combined with the file-serving routes' permissive allowlist (servePublicFiles allows .md/.pdf or the literal name 'incident-support.kdbx'), this is a direct data exfiltration channel.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nRemove serveIndex calls and the public mounts entirely. Move secrets out of the repo. Restrict any operational endpoints to internal networks with auth."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "7.5",
                "tags": [
                  "directory_listing",
                  "info_disclosure",
                  "tier2"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-548"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A05:2021-Security Misconfiguration"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-017",
              "name": "SSRF + stored XSS chain in /profile/image/url",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "SSRF + stored XSS chain in /profile/image/url"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The user-supplied `imageUrl` is fetched server-side with no scheme, host, or DNS restriction. An attacker can probe internal services (cloud metadata at 169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/, internal admin panels, redis, etc.) and either receive the body back via image content or use timing/error oracles. If fetch fails, the URL is then stored as the user's profileImage and rendered into CSP/HTML — yielding stored XSS via the CSP-string injection chain with JS-AUDIT-009."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Validate URL: require https scheme, resolve DNS and reject RFC1918/loopback/link-local. Use an outbound proxy with allowlist. Re-encode/store only the resulting image bytes, never the raw URL.",
                "markdown": "## SSRF + stored XSS chain in /profile/image/url\n\n**CWE:** CWE-918\n\n**OWASP:** A10:2021-Server-Side Request Forgery\n\n### Exploitation\n\nThe user-supplied `imageUrl` is fetched server-side with no scheme, host, or DNS restriction. An attacker can probe internal services (cloud metadata at 169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/, internal admin panels, redis, etc.) and either receive the body back via image content or use timing/error oracles. If fetch fails, the URL is then stored as the user's profileImage and rendered into CSP/HTML — yielding stored XSS via the CSP-string injection chain with JS-AUDIT-009.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nValidate URL: require https scheme, resolve DNS and reject RFC1918/loopback/link-local. Use an outbound proxy with allowlist. Re-encode/store only the resulting image bytes, never the raw URL."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.6",
                "tags": [
                  "ssrf",
                  "xss",
                  "tier2"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-918"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A10:2021-Server-Side Request Forgery"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-018",
              "name": "NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in trackOrder",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in trackOrder"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MarsDB's $where passes the string into a Function() constructor (Dependabot DEP-005 \"Command Injection in marsdb\"). With the 60-char truncated path the attacker can send `' || 1 || '` to dump all orders, or supply `'; return process.mainModule.require('child_process').execSync('id'); //` style payloads for remote code execution inside the Node process. CodeQL alerts 22/23 flag the same."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Replace MarsDB with a maintained store; do not use $where; query with a strict equality predicate on validated ids.",
                "markdown": "## NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in trackOrder\n\n**CWE:** CWE-94\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\nMarsDB's $where passes the string into a Function() constructor (Dependabot DEP-005 \"Command Injection in marsdb\"). With the 60-char truncated path the attacker can send `' || 1 || '` to dump all orders, or supply `'; return process.mainModule.require('child_process').execSync('id'); //` style payloads for remote code execution inside the Node process. CodeQL alerts 22/23 flag the same.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nReplace MarsDB with a maintained store; do not use $where; query with a strict equality predicate on validated ids."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "8.6",
                "tags": [
                  "nosql_injection",
                  "code_injection",
                  "tier2"
                ],
                "precision": "high",
                "cwe": [
                  "CWE-94"
                ],
                "owasp": [
                  "A03:2021-Injection"
                ],
                "triage": "confirmed"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "JS-AUDIT-019",
              "name": "NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in showProductReviews",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in showProductReviews"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Same MarsDB $where issue. An attacker can drive the server into a long-running blocking sleep (the route exposes a global `sleep` helper, deliberately for DoS), exfiltrate timing oracles, and combined with prototype walking, reach process objects."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Recommended fix: Replace MarsDB / drop $where. Validate `id` is an integer.",
                "markdown": "## NoSQL $where JavaScript injection in showProductReviews\n\n**CWE:** CWE-94\n\n**OWASP:** A03:2021-Injection\n\n### Exploitation\n\nSame MarsDB $where issue. An attacker can drive the server into a long-running blocking sleep (the route exposes a global `sleep` helper, deliberately for DoS), exfiltrate timing oracles, and combined with prototype walking, reach process objects.\n\n### Recommended Fix\n\nReplace MarsDB / drop $where. Validate `id` is an integer."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
